<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{toiukotoha}}}} changes a sentence into a noun clause. It is used in cases where the speaker views the contents of @Splain{{}} at a conceptual level.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{toiukotoha}}}} can be used when @Splain{{}} is unlikely or impossible.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he}}gakono@FG{{@KJ{{}}:atsumari}}ni@FG{{@KJ{{come}}:ko}}nai@EM{{toiukotoha}}@FG{{@KJ{{consider}}:kanga}}erarenai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is unthinkable that he won't come to this meeting.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{toiukotoha}}}} can be used when the speaker concludes or attempts to conclude something from @Splain{{}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{hand^paper}}:tegami}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{}}:modo}}te@KJ{{come}}ta@EM{{toiukotoha}}@KJ{{he^woman}}hamoukono@FG{{@KJ{{dwell^place}}:juusho}}nihainaitoiukotoda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The fact that the letter came back means that she no longer lives at this address.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<a href="grammar-koto-wa.html">@HI{{koto}}</a> and @HI{{@EM{{toiukotoha}}}} differ in a number of respects:

<ul>
<li> @HI{{koto}} cannot be used if something is untrue or highly unlikely.
<li> If the speaker knows something through direct experience, only @HI{{koto}} is acceptable.
</ul>
</p>

<p>
When something is likely to happen, either expression is acceptable.
</p>

<p>
When verbs such as @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{emotion}}:kan}}jiru}} and @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{need^request}}:youkyuu}}suru}} are used @Splain{{}} will be concrete and so @HI{{koto}} should be used.
</p>

<p>
When verbs such as @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{transmit}}:tsuta}}eru}} and @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{hear}}:ki}}ku}} are used, either @HI{{koto}} or @HI{{toiukotoha}} can be used.
</p>

